  "insights": {
    "title": "Insights on Child Discipline",
    "subtitle": "Children aged 1 to 14 years by child disciplining methods experienced during the last one month, Philippines, 2022 and 2025.",
    "overview": "The 2025 national picture shows broad movement away from violent discipline methods, but with major regional and subgroup differences that still matter for policy and interpretation. Any violent discipline method fell from 58.8 in 2022 to 54.7 in 2025, while only non-violent discipline rose from 35.7 to 39.0. Psychological aggression, any physical punishment, and severe physical punishment all declined at the national level. At the same time, the spread across regions remains wide, and regional profiles differ not only in level but also in composition, with some regions driven mainly by psychological aggression and others by higher physical punishment. The result is a national improvement pattern that is real but uneven, and not well represented by averages alone.",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "Regional spread remains wide even as national levels improve",
        "body": "In 2025, any violent discipline method ranges from 32.7 in BARMM and 34.9 in Central Visayas to 70.9 in Davao Region, with Cagayan Valley at 66.8 and both Bicol Region and Caraga at 66.4. That is a 38.2-point spread between the highest and lowest regional values. This wide dispersion means the national figure of 54.7 sits in the middle of very different regional realities. Regions at the upper end are not minor deviations from the average; they are substantially higher environments of exposure."
      },
      {
        "heading": "High and low regions are not all high or low for the same reasons",
        "body": "Regional differences are structural, not just rank-order differences. Davao Region's high any violent discipline level (70.9) is paired with very high psychological aggression (60.3) and high any physical punishment (44.7), but relatively low severe physical punishment (1.2). Cagayan Valley is also high on any violent discipline (66.8), with both very high psychological aggression (55.8) and the highest any physical punishment (47.2). At the lower end, BARMM (32.7) and Central Visayas (34.9) combine lower physical punishment levels with lower psychological aggression. These contrasts show that similarly high headline levels can come from different mixes of component behaviors."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Regional change from 2022 to 2025 is uneven, not uniform",
        "body": "The direction of regional change is mixed. There are very large declines in some places, including Zamboanga Peninsula (72.3 to 41.9), Central Visayas (59.9 to 34.9), and Ilocos Region (66.3 to 52.3). But several regions moved in the opposite direction, including BARMM (28.3 to 32.7), Caraga (59.7 to 66.4), and Davao Region (69.2 to 70.9). This pattern indicates that the national decline is carried by concentrated improvements in specific regions rather than a broad, parallel drop everywhere. Regional context therefore remains central to interpretation."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Age profile points to higher violent-discipline exposure in middle childhood",
        "body": "By age, any violent discipline method is lower for ages 1-2 (42.3), higher for ages 3-4 (59.2) and 5-9 (58.5), and somewhat lower again for ages 10-14 (53.1). Any physical punishment follows a similar shape, peaking at ages 3-4 (46.2) and remaining high at ages 5-9 (42.2). This suggests that middle-childhood years carry higher exposure than early toddler ages, while the oldest group has lower physical punishment despite still elevated psychological aggression."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Sex and residence differences are present but not identical in direction",
        "body": "Male children show higher exposure than female children for any violent discipline method (57.1 vs 52.0), any physical punishment (38.9 vs 32.9), and psychological aggression (45.4 vs 41.5). By residence, urban areas have higher any violent discipline (56.2 vs 53.1) and higher physical punishment (39.1 vs 32.9), while rural areas have slightly higher only non-violent discipline (40.8 vs 37.4). These are not opposite systems, but they do suggest that aggregate urban-rural differences are partly driven by the physical-punishment component."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Education and wealth gradients are non-linear rather than monotonic",
        "body": "The socioeconomic pattern is not a simple straight gradient. For wealth quintiles, any violent discipline is highest in the fourth quintile (60.4) and lower in both the poorest (53.4) and richest (47.2) groups. Across educational attainment, the highest levels are seen in groups such as Grades 7-10 (58.1) and post-secondary (58.8), while no education is lower (46.1). These patterns indicate that differences by education and wealth are real but shaped by subgroup composition and behavior mix, not a single monotonic ladder."
      }
    ],
    "takeaways": [
      "National violent-discipline exposure declined between 2022 and 2025, but the country still shows large regional divides.",
      "Regional differences reflect different behavior mixes, not just different intensity of one indicator.",
      "Middle-childhood ages, boys, and urban settings show higher exposure on key violent-discipline measures.",
      "Education and wealth patterns are non-linear, so subgroup interpretation should avoid simple rich-poor or low-high schooling assumptions."
    ]
  },
